The '''Northwest Straits Commission''' was established by [[United States Congress|US Congress]] in 1998 <ref>Testerman, Shelly. "County's marine resources inventoried." Port Townsend & Jefferson County Leader 28 June 2000.</ref> as the Northwest Straits Advisory Commission (referred to as the ‘‘Commission’’) in the [[Northwest Straits Marine Conservation Initiative]] Act.<ref>105th Congress. (1998, November 13). Title IV . Public Law 105-384, p. 9.</ref> The Commission, based at [[Padilla Bay]] National Estuarine Reserve, is administered by the [[Washington State Department of Ecology]] <ref>Puget Sound Water Quality Action Team. "New Initiative Tackles 'Tough Problems' to Protect, Restore Marine Resources." Sound Waves 2000.</ref> and provides base funding for seven [[Marine Resources Committees]] (MRCs) in [[Whatcom County, Washington|Whatcom]], [[Skagit County, Washington|Skagit]], [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]], San Juan, Island, Jefferson and [[Clallam]] counties. The Commission includes state appointees, representatives of seven MRC counties,<ref>Geluso, James. "Federal grant may pinpoint ghost nets ." Skagit Valley Herald 30 10 2001.</ref> a tribal respresentative and a representative from Puget Sound Partnership.<ref>Murray- Metcalf Northwest Straits Citizens Advisory Commission. (1998). Report to Convenors. Seattle: Washington Sea Grant Program, University of Washington.</ref>
